terms.value: The scripps research institute, jupiter, Florida

description: the project presents solution analysis of PPARγ H12 conformational mobility driven by pharmaceutically distinct compounds and sequence specific regulatory peptides by label-free quantitative cross-linking mass spectrometry. This study reveals a model of ligand-dependent antagonism of PPARγ by precisely characterizing H12 mobility as a function of ligand and peptide bound.

modifications.name: No PTMs are included in the dataset

terms.name: Reference
terms.value: Zheng J, Corzo C, Chang MR, Shang J, Lam VQ, Brust R, Blayo AL, Bruning JB, Kamenecka TM, Kojetin DJ, Griffin PR. Chemical Crosslinking Mass Spectrometry Reveals the Conformational Landscape of the Activation Helix of PPARγ; a Model for Ligand-Dependent Antagonism. Structure. 2018

title: Chemical crosslinking mass spectrometry reveals the conformational landscape of the activation helix of PPARγ; a model for ligand-dependent antagonism
